reg("am", "Valuation Techniques",
    technical="• DCF valuation: project FCF = EBIT(1-t) + D&A - CapEx - ΔWC; discount at WACC; terminal value via Gordon Growth or exit multiples\n• Comparable company analysis: EV/EBITDA, P/E, P/B, P/S multiples from peer group with adjustments for growth, margins, risk\n• Precedent transactions: acquisition multiples paid in similar past deals — includes control premium\n• LBO analysis: determine max purchase price given target IRR (15-20%), leverage (4-6x EBITDA), exit multiple\n• Sum-of-the-parts: value each business segment separately using appropriate multiples or DCF",
    behavioral="• Show how you select the right valuation methodology for the situation — no one-size-fits-all\n• Discuss importance of understanding business drivers before applying any model\n• Explain how you sanity-check outputs: compare to market cap, check industry multiples, test assumptions\n• Demonstrate awareness of common pitfalls: terminal value dominance in DCF, stale comps, ignoring debt-like items\n• Mention the art vs science balance — valuation is more art at inflection points or for unique businesses",
    conceptual="• Valuation is the process of determining the present value of expected future cash flows\n• Different methods produce different ranges because each makes different assumptions about growth, risk, and comparability\n• DCF is theoretically purest but highly sensitive to terminal value assumptions (often 60-80% of total value)\n• Multiples are market-driven but reflect current sentiment — can be misleading at market extremes\n• No single method is correct — triangulate across methods for a valuation range",
    practical="• For DCF: project 5-year cash flows, use WACC = risk-free + beta × equity risk premium (10-12% typical for S&P 500)\n• For comps: select 8-12 relevant peers, calculate median multiples, adjust for size/growth differences\n• For precedent transactions: screen last 3 years, match by industry and deal size, consider control premium (20-30% typical)\n• Always cross-check: DCF output vs. current trading multiple — large discrepancies signal issues\n• Scenario analysis: base case, bull case (+20% revenue), bear case (-15% margins)")

