reg("markets", "Risk Assessment",
    technical="• Value at Risk (VaR): 95%/99% confidence, 1-day/10-day holding period — estimates max loss under normal markets\n• Expected Shortfall (CVaR): average loss beyond VaR — captures tail risk better than VaR\n• Stress testing: historical scenarios (2008, 2020) and hypothetical scenarios (rate shock, oil spike)\n• Sensitivity analysis: delta (price change), beta (market correlation), duration (rate sensitivity), spread sensitivity\n• Scenario matrix: combine multiple risk factors (e.g., equity down 20% + rates up 100bp + credit spreads widen)",
    behavioral="• Discuss that risk assessment should be forward-looking, not just backward-looking\n• Explain how you use multiple risk measures because each has blind spots (VaR misses tail risk)\n• Demonstrate awareness that models are simplifications — always question assumptions\n• Show experience with risk systems and reporting: Bloomberg PORT, RiskMetrics, proprietary tools\n• Emphasize that risk assessment is an ongoing process, not a one-time calculation",
    conceptual="• Risk is the possibility of loss — all financial decisions involve some degree of risk\n• Different risk measures capture different aspects: VaR for normal markets, stress tests for crises\n• Correlations change in stress — diversification fails when most needed\n• Model risk: all risk models are wrong, some are useful (Box's aphorism)\n• Liquidity risk is the most dangerous — positions that can't be exited amplify losses")

reg("markets", "Stress Management",
    behavioral="• Maintain disciplined risk limits — they're designed for volatile markets when emotional control is hardest\n• Take breaks during trading hours — sustained focus over 6-8 hours leads to mental fatigue\n• Keep a trading journal: review what worked and what didn't to learn from mistakes\n• Separate good decisions from good outcomes — a good trade can lose money and vice versa\n• Physical health: regular exercise, adequate sleep, no trading on no sleep or after alcohol",
    conceptual="• Trading is a performance profession — mental state directly impacts decision quality\n• The biggest losses often follow a string of wins (overconfidence effect)\n• Loss aversion: losses hurt ~2x more than equivalent gains feel good — leads to holding losers too long\n• Recency bias: recent experiences are overweighted in decision making\n• Discipline and process separate professional traders from retail speculators",
    practical="• Set maximum daily loss limits: hit the limit, stop trading for the day\n• After a large losing trade, reduce position size by 50% for 3 sessions\n• Use checklists before entering trades to avoid impulsive decisions\n• Practice mindfulness or meditation to improve focus and emotional regulation\n• Have a post-market review routine: what worked, what didn't, what to do differently")

