reg("am", "Active vs Passive Management Debate",
    technical="• Active management relies on manager skill to select securities and time the market to outperform benchmarks — higher fees (0.5-1.5%), higher turnover, concentrated positions\n• Passive management tracks market indices via ETFs or index funds — low fees (0.03-0.10%), lower turnover (tax-efficient), beta-only exposure\n• SPIVA study shows 85-90% of active large-cap US equity managers underperform the S&P 500 over 10+ years\n• Active can outperform in inefficient markets (small caps, emerging markets, distressed debt) where information advantages exist\n• The choice depends on market efficiency belief, cost sensitivity, and the investor's ability to select skilled managers",
    behavioral="• Demonstrate understanding of both sides: active offers potential alpha but most managers fail to deliver consistently\n• Show how you evaluate managers: risk-adjusted returns vs benchmark, rolling period consistency, style drift, fee structures\n• Discuss the role of passive for core market exposure and active for satellite positions seeking outperformance\n• Show awareness of factor investing as a middle ground — rules-based exposure to risk premia at lower cost than active\n• Explain your personal investment philosophy and how you apply active/passive decisions in practice",
    conceptual="• Active vs passive is a fundamental debate in investment management with strong arguments on both sides\n• Market efficiency determines whether active management can consistently generate alpha\n• Most evidence favors passive for retail investors but skilled active managers exist and can add significant value\n• The rise of factor investing blurs the line — rules-based factors are active strategies in passive vehicles\n• Investor behavior and fees are the most important determinants of eventual returns",
    case="• For a client with low cost sensitivity and high return expectations: recommended 70/30 split active/passive with core passive for beta and active sleeves for alpha\n• For a cost-sensitive client: primarily passive with low-cost factor tilts (value, momentum, quality) via smart beta ETFs\n• Past performance analysis: evaluate rolling 3-year relative performance, factor-adjusted alpha, and manager consistency over full market cycles\n• Risk considerations: active introduces manager risk (key person, style drift), tracking error, and higher turnover costs")

reg("am", "Market Timing vs Time in Market",
    technical="• Time in market consistently outperforms market timing over long horizons — staying invested captures compounding and avoids missing the best days\n• Missing the 10 best trading days per decade (which are often clustered around major rallies) reduces 20-year returns by 50%+ (time is more important than timing)\n• Market timing requires correctly predicting both exit and re-entry points — even professional fund managers fail to time the market consistently\n• Dollar-cost averaging reduces timing risk by spreading entry across multiple time points — useful for lump sums but sacrifices some upside\n• Systematic rebalancing (quarterly or threshold-based) naturally captures timing-like benefits: selling what's expensive, buying what's cheap",
    behavioral="• Discuss the academic evidence: time in market beats timing over long horizons — missed best days dramatically reduce returns\n• Show understanding that market timing is emotionally difficult — requires going against the crowd (buying when others are fearful)\n• Explain the practical difficulty: you need to be right about both the exit AND the re-entry point\n• Mention the dollar-cost averaging approach as a compromise: not pure timing but reduced timing risk\n• Discuss how rebalancing provides a systematic timing mechanism without market prediction",
    case="• Client has $1M cash lump sum and is worried about investing at market peak — recommend dollar-cost averaging over 6-12 months with remainder in T-bills\n• Historical analysis: lump sum beat DCA ~66% of the time over 10-year horizons but DCA reduces regret risk for emotionally sensitive clients\n• For cash flow investment (monthly 401k): time-in-market dominates — never try to time regular contributions\n• Stress scenario: if market drops 20% right after full investment, acknowledge the timing risk was real but long-term recovery offsets")

reg("am", "Behavioral Biases in Investing",
    technical="• Loss aversion: losses hurt ~2x more than equivalent gains feel good → leads to selling winners too early and holding losers too long (disposition effect)\n• Overconfidence: investors overestimate their ability to predict markets or select stocks → leads to excessive trading (60%+ annual turnover correlation with underperformance)\n• Confirmation bias: seeking information that confirms existing views while ignoring contradictory evidence → leads to concentrated positions and missed risk signals\n• Anchoring: fixating on a reference point (purchase price, 52-week high) → leads to poor buy/sell decisions based on irrelevant past prices\n• Herding: following the crowd into popular trades or sectors → leads to bubble buying and panic selling at extremes",
    conceptual="• Behavioral finance explains how psychological biases cause investors to make suboptimal decisions\n• These biases are systematic and predictable — they create market inefficiencies that disciplined investors can exploit\n• Awareness of one's own biases is the first step to mitigating them — use checklists, systematic processes, and pre-commitment to trading rules\n• The best defense is a disciplined investment process with pre-defined rules for entry, exit, position sizing, and rebalancing\n• Advisors provide value primarily through behavioral coaching — keeping clients invested during drawdowns and preventing panic decisions")

reg("am", "Risk-Adjusted Performance Measurement",
    technical="• Sharpe ratio: (portfolio return - risk-free rate) / standard deviation — measures return per unit of total risk; >1 good, >2 excellent, higher is better\n• Sortino ratio: (portfolio return - risk-free rate) / downside deviation — only penalizes downside volatility; better for strategies with asymmetric returns (options, trend-following)\n• Information ratio: (portfolio return - benchmark return) / tracking error — measures active return per unit of active risk; >0.5 good, >1 excellent\n• Jensen's alpha: actual return minus CAPM-expected return (Rf + β×(Rm-Rf)) — measures manager skill vs systematic risk exposure\n• Treynor ratio: (portfolio return - risk-free rate) / β (systematic risk) — like Sharpe but uses beta instead of total risk; best for well-diversified portfolios",
    conceptual="• Risk-adjusted returns measure how much return an investment generated per unit of risk taken\n• Different metrics are appropriate for different contexts: Sharpe for total portfolio evaluation, Sortino for downside-risk-sensitive investors, Information for active managers vs benchmarks\n• No single metric tells the full story — use multiple metrics and qualitative judgment\n• Higher returns do not necessarily mean better performance if they come with proportionally higher risk\n• Risk-adjusted metrics should be evaluated over full market cycles (5+ years) to capture both bull and bear market behavior")

reg("am", "Risk Assessment",
    technical="• Quantitative risk measures: standard deviation (15-20% for equities, 5-8% for bonds), beta (market sensitivity), VaR (95/99% daily/10-day), expected shortfall, max drawdown\n• Fundamental risk analysis: business model risk, competitive position durability, financial leverage (Debt/EBITDA > 4x is concerning), management quality, regulatory exposure\n• Scenario analysis: base case, downside case (recession +20% earnings drop + multiple contraction), upside case (strong growth + multiple expansion)\n• Concentration risk: single position >5% of portfolio, sector >20%, currency, factor exposure analysis\n• Liquidity risk: position size vs average daily volume (<5% of daily volume for easy exit), time to liquidate in stressed markets",
    conceptual="• Risk assessment evaluates the potential for loss across multiple dimensions: market, credit, liquidity, operational, concentration\n• Quantitative measures are necessary but insufficient — qualitative judgment about business quality and competitive dynamics is equally important\n• The most dangerous risks are the ones you don't see: tail risks, hidden leverage, counterparty exposure, model limitations\n• Scenario and stress testing identify how the portfolio behaves under extreme but plausible conditions\n• Risk assessment should be ongoing, not a one-time exercise — update as markets, companies, and economic conditions evolve")

reg("quant", "Quantitative Research Process",
    technical="• Hypothesis generation: identify market inefficiency (momentum, value, carry, mean reversion) → develop testable hypothesis with clear economic rationale\n• Data collection: source high-quality historical data (CRSP, Compustat, Bloomberg), clean for errors, adjust for corporate actions and splits\n• Model development: feature engineering, model selection (linear, tree-based, neural network), regularization to prevent overfitting\n• Backtesting: simulate strategy on historical data with realistic transaction costs, walk-forward validation, out-of-sample testing\n• Production deployment: paper trade → limit-live → full deployment with continuous monitoring for strategy decay and regime changes",
    behavioral="• Start with a clear economic story — a strategy without a reason for existence is just data mining\n• Use walk-forward analysis: optimize on rolling windows, test on unseen forward data — the most robust validation approach for time series\n• Transaction costs are the biggest gap between backtest and reality — model them realistically including slippage and market impact\n• Test for robustness across sub-periods, market regimes (bull/bear/volatile), and parameter variations\n• Document everything: assumptions, data sources, methodology changes, and validation results — reproducibility is critical",
    conceptual="• Quantitative research applies scientific method to financial markets: hypothesis, data, model, validation, deployment\n• The biggest risk is overfitting — finding patterns in noise that fail out-of-sample\n• Simple models often beat complex ones after transaction costs — parsimony should be a guiding principle\n• The research process must be disciplined and systematic — emotions and hunches belong in discretionary, not quant\n• Edges decay as they attract capital — continuous research is required, not a one-time strategy development")

reg("quant", "Backtesting Methodology",
    technical="• Walk-forward analysis: divide data into training (60%), validation (20%), test (20%), optimize parameters on training, validate performance on test, repeat on rolling windows\n• Transaction cost modeling: commission (per share/trade), slippage (based on volume and volatility), market impact (Almgren-Chriss model or 1/2 spread), financing costs for leveraged positions\n• Biases to avoid: look-ahead (using future info in signal calculation), survivorship (only including current index members), selection (cherry-picking time periods), optimization (multiple tests inflate false positives)\n• Performance metrics: Sharpe ratio, max drawdown, Calmar ratio, hit rate, profit factor, average win/loss ratio, consistency across sub-periods\n• Robustness checks: parameter sensitivity (how stable are results to small parameter changes), monte carlo simulation of entry timing, regime sub-period analysis",
    behavioral="• The most important rule of backtesting: if it looks too good to be true, it probably is (Sharpe > 3 is almost certainly overfit)\n• Test the strategy in the context of transaction costs that are higher than you expect — backtest with 2-3x realistic costs\n• Always run out-of-sample testing before any real-money deployment — the first day of live trading is the ultimate test\n• Beware of data mining bias: if you test 100 variations, 5 will appear significant at 95% confidence — use multiple testing corrections (Bonferroni, FDR)\n• Backtest is not a prediction — it's a historical simulation that may or may not reflect future conditions",
    conceptual="• Backtesting evaluates a trading strategy's performance on historical data before committing real capital\n• Good backtesting reveals a strategy's characteristics; bad backtesting tells you what you want to hear\n• The key question is not 'what was the backtested Sharpe?' but 'will this strategy work forward?'\n• Realistic transaction cost modeling separates useful backtests from dangerous ones\n• No backtest can predict regime changes — a strategy that worked in low-volatility markets may fail in high-volatility environments")

reg("quant", "Model Validation",
    technical="• In-sample vs out-of-sample: split data chronologically (not randomly) — train on 2010-2020, test on 2021-2025; walk-forward optimization retrains on rolling windows\n• Benchmarks: compare model performance against simple baselines (buy-and-hold, equally weighted, last period return) — if ML doesn't beat a naive baseline, it's not useful\n• Sensitivity analysis: test how output changes with small input perturbations — linear models should be stable, non-linear models should be tested for robustness\n• Residual analysis: check model errors for patterns, autocorrelation, heteroskedasticity — patterns in error indicate model misspecification\n• Stress testing: evaluate model performance under extreme scenarios — 2008 crisis, 2020 COVID crash, 2022 rate shock, periods of extreme volatility",
    behavioral="• Model validation is not a one-time step but a continuous process — models degrade as market regimes change\n• Start with the simplest model possible (linear regression, moving average) before adding complexity\n• The modeler's biggest bias is confirmation bias — testing until a result confirms what you want to believe\n• Independent validation by a separate team is best practice — no one validates their own model objectively\n• Document model limitations explicitly: what conditions does the model work in, and when does it fail?",
    conceptual="• Model validation ensures a model performs as expected before deployment and continues to perform over time\n• Every model is wrong in some ways — the goal is to understand the nature and magnitude of the errors\n• Simpler models are easier to validate, understand, and monitor — complexity should have a demonstrable benefit\n• Model risk (losses from incorrect model assumptions) is a recognized risk type under Basel framework\n• Validation findings should lead to model adjustments, not be ignored because 'the model needs to go live'")


